05511nam a22009135i 9780228014881DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20222022xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280148817 a10.1515/97802280148812doi  a(DE-B1597)656115  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aF1059.7.G3bB79 2022 7aHIS0060002bisacsh04a971.3/004312231 aBryce, Benjamin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Boundaries of Ethnicity :bGerman Immigration and the Language of Belonging in Ontario /cBenjamin Bryce. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource :b10 photos, 4 tables, 1 map  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in Ethnic History00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures and Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Note on the Cover Image -- tIntroduction: The Boundaries of Ethnicity -- tThe State and Ethnicity -- tMaking English Canada: French and German Schools in Ontario -- tMaking English Canada: French and German Schools in Ontario -- tMaking Ethnic Spaces -- tTeaching Language, Teaching Religion: St Jerome’s and Waterloo Lutheran Colleges -- tThe Boundaries of Religion: German Lutheranism in Ontario and the United States -- tEthnic Practice -- tThe Language of Religion: Children and Denominational Identity -- tThe Rise of Bilingualism -- tConclusion: Citizenship, Ethnicity, and Pluralism -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries, European settlers from diverse backgrounds transformed Ontario. By 1881, German speakers made up almost ten per cent of the province’s population and the German language was spoken in businesses, public schools, churches, and homes. German speakers in Ontario – children, parents, teachers, and religious groups – used their everyday practices and community institutions to claim a space for bilingualism and religious diversity within Canadian society. In The Boundaries of Ethnicity Benjamin Bryce considers what it meant to be German in Ontario between 1880 and 1930. He explores how the children of immigrants acquired and negotiated the German language and how religious communities relied on language to reinforce social networks. For the Germans who make up the core of this study, the distinction between insiders and outsiders was often unclear. Boundaries were crossed as often as they were respected. German ethnicity in this period was fluid, and increasingly interventionist government policies and the dynamics of generational change also shaped the boundaries of ethnicity.German speakers, together with immigrants from other countries and Canadians of different ethnic backgrounds, created a framework that defined relationships between the state, the public sphere, ethnic spaces, family, and religion in Canada that would persist through the twentieth century. The Boundaries of Ethnicity uncovers some of the origins of Canadian multiculturalism and government attempts to manage this diversity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aGerman languagexSocial aspectszOntarioxHistoryy19th century. 0aGerman languagexSocial aspectszOntarioxHistoryy20th century. 0aGerman languagezOntarioxReligious aspectsxHistoryy19th century. 0aGerman languagezOntarioxReligious aspectsxHistoryy20th century. 0aGermanszOntarioxEthnic identityxHistoryy19th century. 0aGermanszOntarioxEthnic identityxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh  aCatholic.  aGerman-Canadians.  aGerman.  aGermanophone.  aLutheran.  aSunday School.  aWorld War.  aadaptation.  aassimilati